posts.name: Andrew Torrance
posts.cooked:
Team 254 is proud to present their Technical Binder and Code for the 2024 Robot: VORTEX.  

The binder includes:
- A link to the full technical binder
- A Behind the Bumpers video
- A match video showcasing the robot in action
- Access to the team's GitHub repository containing the code

Additional resources include links to previous discussions on the robot reveal, turret prototyping, and pit judging.

posts.name: Kylan Siwinski
posts.cooked: Just throwing this out here now that the tech binder is finally released - our old amp mech could do trick shots! We ended up removing cat tongue tape from the bottom roller to trap better, but this got rid of the backward scoring capability so we never got to run this at competition.

posts.name: Mark Sheridan
posts.cooked: We sanded the polycarbonate plate using an orbital sander, which worked well for these notes. Teflon from McMaster was used for other polycarbonate parts. The ultra low friction tape is expensive, but we used cheaper alternatives for prototypes.
The material on the backside of my shooter appears to be a single curved piece.

posts.name: Kylan Siwinski
posts.cooked: The backside of the shooter was constructed primarily from two components: an exterior nylon 3D printed ramp created using an HP Multi Jet Fusion printer at J&J Medtech, and an internal 1/32-inch bent aluminum plate, both coated with Teflon tape to enhance friction reduction. The aluminum remained stationary while the 3D-printed ramp moved with the hood, offering support to the aluminum even when positioned nearly horizontally.
Beautiful robot as always. Watching the omni-feed turret on Einstein was an absolute pleasure. Could not possibly optimize it further!

posts.name: Brian Wagg
posts.cooked: The text is: The tech binder references that the energy chain you used for the turret (the “BIGUS”) is 3D printed and a custom size for this specific application; Could you provide some detail on how you drew the energy chain, and what method was used to print it (desktop printer, markforged, HP multijet etc)? For designing the energy chain, was it as “simple” as downloading a vendor’s CAD model of an existing chain, and adjusting for the overall dimensions needed to house the shooter subsystems wiring? Or was the design process more involved than that?

posts.name: Noah Howard
posts.cooked:
The text is:  
The layout of the chain was planned by prototyping it on a table with specific constraints marked out such as bellypan dimensions positions of electronics and required space. This helped determine the number of links positioning of the tensioner and other components which were later transferred to CAD software. A photo of the prototype is available at [link].  

The links were designed by adapting an existing model from Igus and modifying its dimensions to suit our needs. After strengthening the tabs they were printed separately on the HP MultiJet printer and assembled into the final product.
How long did those prints take? Quite interesting in terms of the speed of the MultiJet.

posts.name: Mark Sheridan
posts.cooked:
When we borrow JnJ’s MJF, we receive a batch, which motivates us to utilize the entire print volume effectively. The volume was sufficient for both the robots and spares, taking approximately 1 day to complete.  

Edit: To explain how an MJF works briefly, it constructs layers of powder, making print time proportional to how much volume is utilized. Based on our part sizes, it was optimal to fully utilize the volume (completely filled with powder). The efficiency of the process increases as you incorporate more parts. This innovative technology proved exceptionally effective, and we were fortunate to use it multiple times this season.

What is the reasoning for running the intake rollers slower than the drivetrain’s free speed? Also, [image](https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/0/4/04f714d10bd20dd5dc313c25ca7a58b0e6e04bc3.png) REV robotics hmm…
